android.permission.READ_PHONE_STATE.description: Allows the application to access the phone features of the device. An application with this permission can determine the phone number and serial number of this phone, whether a call is active, the number that call is connected to and so on.

android.permission.USE_BIOMETRIC.description: Allows an app to use device supported biometric modalities.

android.permission.INTERNET.description: Allows an application to create network sockets.

android.permission.ACCESS_NETWORK_STATE.description: Allows an application to view the status of all networks.

android.permission.CAMERA.description: Allows application to take pictures and videos with the camera. This allows the application to collect images that the camera is seeing at any time.

android.permission.WRITE_EXTERNAL_STORAG.description: Allows an application to write to external storage.

android.permission.READ_CONTACTS.description: Allows an application to read all of the contact (address) data stored on your phone. Malicious applications can use this to send your data to other people.

android.permission.GET_TASKS.description: Allows application to retrieve information about currently and recently running tasks. May allow malicious applications to discover private information about other applications.

android.permission.RECEIVE_BOOT_COMPLETE.description: Allows an application to start itself as soon as the system has finished booting. This can make it take longer to start the phone and allow the application to slow down the overall phone by always running.

android.permission.WAKE_LOCK.description: Allows an application to prevent the phone from going to sleep.

android.permission.FOREGROUND_SERVICE.description: Allows a regular application to use Service.startForeground

android.permission.READ_EXTERNAL_STORAGE.description: Allows an application to read from external storage.

android.permission.USE_FINGERPRINT.description: This constant was deprecated in API level 28. Applications should request USE_BIOMETRIC instead

com.google.android.c2dm.permission.RECEI.description: Permission for cloud to device messaging.

nx.description: The shared object has NX bit set. This marks a memory page non-executable making attacker injected shellcode non-executable.

stack_canary.description: This shared object has a stack canary value added to the stack so that it will be overwritten by a stack buffer that overflows the return address. This allows detection of overflows by verifying the integrity of the canary before function return.

relocation_readonly.description: This shared object has full RELRO enabled. RELRO ensures that the GOT cannot be overwritten in vulnerable ELF binaries. In Full RELRO, the entire GOT (.got and .got.plt both) is marked as read-only.

rpath.description: The shared object does not have run-time search path or RPATH set.

runpath.description: The shared object does not have RUNPATH set.

fortify.description: The shared object does not have any fortified functions. Fortified functions provides buffer overflow checks against glibc's commons insecure functions like strcpy, gets etc. Use the compiler option -D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=2 to fortify functions.

file_analysis.finding: Certificate/Key files hardcoded inside the app.

metadata.description: Query Database of SMS, Contacts etc

metadata.cwe: CWE-312 Cleartext Storage of Sensitive Information
metadata.description: Files may contain hardcoded sensitive informations like usernames, passwords, keys etc.
The App logs information. Sensitive information should never be logged.
metadata.cwe: CWE-532 Insertion of Sensitive Information into Log File
CWE-327 Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm
metadata.description: MD5 is a weak hash known to have hash collisions.

metadata.cwe: CWE-327 Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm
metadata.description: SHA-1 is a weak hash known to have hash collisions.
This App uses SSL certificate pinning to detect or  prevent MITM attacks in secure communication channel.
The App uses an insecure Random Number Generator.
metadata.cwe: CWE-330 Use of Insufficiently Random Values

metadata.description: App creates temp file. Sensitive information should never be written into a temp file.
App uses SQLite Database and execute raw SQL query. Untrusted user input in raw SQL queries can cause SQL Injection. Also sensitive information should be encrypted and written to the database.
metadata.cwe: CWE-89 Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')

metadata.description: The App uses ECB mode in Cryptographic encryption algorithm. ECB mode is known to be weak as it results in the same ciphertext for identical blocks of plaintext.
metadata.cwe: CWE-327 Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm

metadata.description: This App copies data to clipboard. Sensitive data should not be copied to clipboard as other applications can access it.
App can read/write to External Storage. Any App can read data written to External Storage.
This App uses SQL Cipher. SQLCipher provides 256-bit AES encryption to sqlite database files.
This App may have root detection capabilities.
Insecure Implementation of SSL. Trusting all the certificates or accepting self signed certificates is a critical Security Hole. This application is vulnerable to MITM attacks
This App may request root (Super User) privileges.

FCS_RBG_EXT.2.1,FCS_RBG_EXT.2.2.choice: The application perform all deterministic random bit generation (DRBG) services in accordance with NIST Special Publication 800-90A using Hash_DRBG. The deterministic RBG is seeded by an entropy source that accumulates entropy from a platform-based DRBG and a software-based noise source, with a minimum of 256 bits of entropy at least equal to the greatest security strength (according to NIST SP 800-57) of the keys and hashes that it will generate.

FCS_CKM.1.1(1).choice: The application generate asymmetric cryptographic keys not in accordance with FCS_CKM.1.1(1) using key generation algorithm RSA schemes and cryptographic key sizes of 1024-bit or lower.

FCS_COP.1.1(1).choice: The application perform encryption/decryption not in accordance with FCS_COP.1.1(1), AES-ECB mode is being used.

FCS_COP.1.1(2).choice: The application perform cryptographic hashing services not in accordance with FCS_COP.1.1(2) and uses the cryptographic algorithm RC2/RC4/MD4/MD5.

FCS_COP.1.1(3).choice: The application perform cryptographic signature services (generation and verification) in accordance with a specified cryptographic algorithm RSA schemes using cryptographic key sizes of 2048-bit or greater.

FCS_COP.1.1(4).choice: The application perform keyed-hash message authentication with cryptographic algorithm ['HMAC-SHA-256'] .

FCS_HTTPS_EXT.1.2.choice: The application implement HTTPS using TLS.

FCS_HTTPS_EXT.1.3.choice: The application notify the user and not establish the connection or request application authorization to establish the connection if the peer certificate is deemed invalid.

FIA_X509_EXT.1.1.choice: The application invoked platform-provided functionality to validate certificates in accordance with the following rules: ['The certificate path must terminate with a trusted CA certificate', 'The application validate a certificate path by ensuring the presence of the basicConstraints extension and that the CA flag is set to TRUE for all CA certificates'].

FIA_X509_EXT.1.2.choice: The application treat a certificate as a CA certificate only if the basicConstraints extension is present and the CA flag is set to TRUE.

FIA_X509_EXT.2.1.choice: The application use X.509v3 certificates as defined by RFC 5280 to support authentication for HTTPS , TLS.

FIA_X509_EXT.2.2.choice: When the application cannot establish a connection to determine the validity of a certificate, the application allow the administrator to choose whether to accept the certificate in these cases or accept the certificate ,or not accept the certificate.

FPT_TUD_EXT.2.1.choice: The application shall be distributed using the format of the platform-supported package manager.

playstore_details.title: MoneyPipe: HD Bitcoin Wallet
playstore_details.description:
MoneyPipe HD multi-currency crypto wallet is unlike any other — it’s not a cloud wallet or exchange. It’s a full-fledged Hierarchical Deterministic wallet with an independent infrastructure. The private keys are always solely under the user’s control and never leave the device.

MoneyPipe HD is an easy-to-use, reliable and secure guide in the world of cryptocurrency that you can use to perform Bitcoin, Ethereum, and other cryptocurrency transactions whenever and wherever you want.

Using our app reduces the risk of hacking and phishing attacks thanks to the heightened security level.

MoneyPipe HD Bitcoin Wallet has no equals, and here is why:


INTERFACE AND STATISTICS 🌌

The MoneyPipe Bitcoin Wallet is focused specifically on comfort and ease-of-use. That is why thousands of users chose the MoneyPipe HD Bitcoin wallet. It’s simple, yet distinguished. It’s intuitive to any person regardless of age and experience.
No complex verifications or other mumbo-jumbo.

🆒Great visual design

ℹ️Full information on current transactions and exchange rates

🔀Transferring and receiving funds to your wallet is very easy


TRANSFER BY PHONE NUMBER 📲


By using the MoneyPipe HD wallet you will no longer put yourself in danger by having to deal with long addresses.

We have developed a unique system that significantly decreases the risks of phishing and trivial mistakes.

The MoneyPipe HD crypto wallet is integrated with the address book, thanks to which, it displays all of your phone contacts, under the condition that they also use our app. Therefore, you can add your friends to the address book and send funds only to trusted individuals.

Also, when sending Bitcoin, Ethereum, or another cryptocurrency to your contacts, you can add any comment to the transaction that the recipient will also see. That is why the app asks for your phone number during registration.

If you do not want to add someone’s phone number to your address book but want to send that person funds via MoneyPipe HD, you can simply enter that person’s phone number into the input field on the “Send” page and perform the payment.


SECURITY🛡

Security features of the MoneyPipe HD Bitcoin wallet include:

🔐PIN
🔐Touch ID / Face ID authorization
🔐Seed phrase

MoneyPipe HD runs exclusively on its own server cluster. All of the information about BTC, ETH or other coin transactions is taken only from our own sources, therefore no external services can access data regarding the user’s actions within the wallet.

Thanks to the HD (Hierarchical Deterministic) technology, our users are provided with an increased level of anonymity and security. This technology not only increases data privacy, but also solves the backup problem.

MoneyPipe HD is a non-custodial wallet which means that the private keys are stored exclusively on the user’s device. They are never transmitted to any third-party servers and can be exported by the user at any time for any cryptocurrency. The same thing can be said about the seed phrase — after you save it and confirm that it will be deleted from your device.

We do our best to protect our users as much as possible.


SOLE OWNERSHIP 👤

When using the MoneyPipe HD Bitcoin Wallet, you and only you control your private keys. Neither the server nor the developers have access to your coins.


ACCESS FROM ANY DEVICE 📱

And finally, you can log into your wallet on any compatible device by using a single seed phrase (secret phrase). You can also use it to restore your entire wallet history and all of its data without exception. But remember: the seed phrase needs to be stored in a very secure place!

✭✭✭✭✭
MoneyPipe HD is the most secure mobile crypto wallet according to cryptor.net

Store your coins the right way!
